Section Summary: Paolo Veronese, born Paolo Caliari in 1528 in Verona, was a great painter known for his unique blend of absurdity and adorability. He was trained by his uncle, Antonio Badile, and developed his skills through diligent practice, including copying the engravings of masters like Albert Durer. Veronese's early works already showed promise, and he quickly gained recognition in Verona and beyond, including a commission from Cardinal Ercole di Gonzaga to paint a picture for the cathedral in Mantua. He eventually outgrew the limited opportunities in Verona and moved to other cities, including Tiene, where he received a commission to decorate a palace. Veronese's love for Venice, where he later settled, had a profound impact on his work, and he became known as the chosen painter of the Most Serene Republic, capturing the city's vibrant colors and joyous spirit in his paintings.
